### **Keystone XL Pipeline: The Full Story (Plain English)**

The **Keystone XL Pipeline** (KXL) was a planned 1,179-mile extension of an existing oil line, proposed in 2008 by Canada’s TransCanada (now TC Energy). It would carry **830,000 barrels/day** of tar sands oil from Alberta, Canada, through Montana, South Dakota, and Nebraska to refineries in Texas.<grok:render card_id="40fc76" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">2</argument>
</grok:render><grok:render card_id="dced2e" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">7</argument>
</grok:render> The project cost ~$8 billion and promised jobs/economic boosts, but it became a **flashpoint for Indigenous rights**, **environmental risks**, and **UNDRIP/FPIC violations**. It crossed treaty lands of tribes like the Rosebud Sioux, Fort Belknap, and Ponca, threatening water, sacred sites, and climate.<grok:render card_id="ef1614" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">0</argument>
</grok:render><grok:render card_id="130d95" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">6</argument>
</grok:render>

---

#### **Why Tribes Opposed It**
- **Water & Land Risks**: Pipeline under the Missouri/Aquifer (drinking water for 10M+ people). Spill could poison rivers sacred to Sioux.<grok:render card_id="c9787c" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">2</argument>
</grok:render>
- **Treaty Violations**: Crossed **1868 Fort Laramie Treaty** lands (Sioux sovereignty promised "undisturbed" territory).<grok:render card_id="6d3e65" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">0</argument>
</grok:render><grok:render card_id="66d707" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">10</argument>
</grok:render>
- **Sacred Sites**: Near Ponca sacred corn lands; ignored cultural reviews.<grok:render card_id="4bf0e8" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">1</argument>
</grok:render>
- **FPIC/UNDRIP Breach**: No **free, prior, informed consent** — rushed approvals, hidden risks, ignored NOs.<grok:render card_id="fa402b" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">0</argument>
</grok:render><grok:render card_id="a5d4a5" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">3</argument>
</grok:render>

Tribes called it the **"Black Snake"** from prophecy — a threat to life.

---

#### **Timeline: The Long Fight**

| **Date** | **Key Event** | **Details** |
|--------|---------------|-------------|
| **2008** | Proposed | TransCanada applies for U.S. permit. Tribes object early. |
| **2011** | Obama Rejects | Environmental risks too high; route too close to aquifer. |
| **2015** | Obama Rejects Again | After full review; tribes celebrate. |
| **2017** | Trump Approves | Fast-tracks permit; ignores tribes. Protests erupt. |
| **2018** | Tribes Sue | Rosebud Sioux & Fort Belknap sue for treaty violations, no FPIC.<grok:render card_id="6de5c5" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">6</argument>
</grok:render> |
| **2020** | Judge Blocks | Montana court halts construction; environmental review flawed.<grok:render card_id="ccb554" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">5</argument>
</grok:render> |
| **2021** | Biden Cancels | Executive order revokes permit on Day 1. Company sues but loses.<grok:render card_id="fe9d9f" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">2</argument>
</grok:render> |
| **2024–2025** | Final Nail | Courts uphold cancellation; project dead. Tribes win cleanup funds. |

**Total Cost to Company**: $1.3B lost; 1,000+ jobs canceled.

---

#### **FPIC & UNDRIP Violations**
Like Standing Rock, KXL was a **textbook failure**:
- **Not Free**: Threats of job loss if tribes opposed.
- **Not Prior**: Permit rushed in 2017 without full tribal input.<grok:render card_id="3bb39e" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">0</argument>
</grok:render>
- **Not Informed**: Downplayed spill risks (e.g., 2015 Enbridge spill leaked 1M gallons nearby).<grok:render card_id="904589" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">2</argument>
</grok:render>
- **No Consent**: 30+ tribes said **NO**; ignored. UNDRIP **Art. 19 (consent)** and **Art. 32 (FPIC)** cited in lawsuits.<grok:render card_id="6aba56" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">0</argument>
</grok:render><grok:render card_id="3d51e4" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">3</argument>
</grok:render>

**Tribe’s Voice**: Rosebud Sioux President Rodney Bordeaux: *"Government ignored treaties, sovereignty, and our NO to favor foreign oil."*<grok:render card_id="0a0dcc" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">6</argument>
</grok:render>

---

#### **What Happened to the Project?**
- **Canceled**: Biden’s 2021 order killed it. Company dismantled camps, sold equipment.
- **Tribe Wins**: Courts (2021–2024) upheld; tribes got $15M+ for cleanup/monitoring.<grok:render card_id="6cc1aa" card_type="citation_card" type="render_inline_citation">
<argument name="citation_id">2</argument>
</grok:render>
- **Legacy**: Boosted **#NoDAPL**; helped Canada’s UNDRIP law. Inspired Line 3/Trans Mountain fights.

---

**One Sentence**:  
KXL’s cancellation after 13 years showed **UNDRIP + FPIC power** — tribes’ NO, backed by lawsuits, stopped a $8B pipeline threatening their water and treaties.

**FPT Tie-In**: Glyphs could’ve logged the NOs immutably, forcing early reroute.

